Beautiful, "complete," comet.  The inner coma was quite bright, and measured ~ 30 arc seconds in diameter.   This inner coma was surrounded by a much fainter outer component ~ 1 arc minute in diameter.  The nearly stellar pseudo-nucleus  at times scintillated like a twinkling star when observed at 79 X.
Reference stars: SAO 119700 used to estimate comet's magnitude.

Comment: Above listed star used to estimate magnitude.  After easily observing this comet two evenings ago in bright moonlight with the 32 cm scope, I was curious to see if it would be visible in a 15 cm scope.  At 02:52 UT, I was just barely able to make out this comet at 38 X, still 35 minutes before the end of astronomical twilight!!  I upped the magnification to 94 X, and had another look at 03:16 UT (three minutes before moonrise), and could see it as elongated in the same PA as the tail, appearing teardrop shaped.
